Discussion
In the present study, we have carried out systematic structural investigations on combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2 catalysts. It has been an endeavor of researchers to reduce the amount of noble metal content without adversely affecting their catalytic properties. Ionic dispersion is an effective way to achieve this. Combustion synthesis provides in a single step ionically dispersed metal on ceria support.
The structure of 0.51 atom % Rh/CeO2 is important, because the maximum Rh loading required is less than 1 atom %. To see how the Rh-related phases evolve with increase in Rh loading, 2 atom% Rh/CeO2 was studied. The XRD pattern of 1% Rh/CeO2 clearly ruled out Rh metal or Rh oxide phases. In the combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2, Rh ion taken in the preparation should be separated either into Rh metal particles or its oxides or Rh ion should be incorporated in the CeO2 matrix. In the preparation, the Rh precursor taken is in the +3 state and Ce4+ and Rh3+ are totally mixed in the ionic state. The combustion of the precursor leading to a flame in the oxidizing atmosphere (air) lasts only for a few seconds. Thus, the high-temperature phase formed is quenched to form the active catalyst. In such a short period of time, separation of Rh ions in the form of Rh2O3 or reduction into Rh metal particles does not seem to occur. However, with an increase in Rh metal concentration (2 atom % Rh) an extremely small amount of Rh metal particles is separated, not Rh2O3. If Rh3+ substitutes for Ce4+ in the CeO2 lattice, then charge neutrality demands oxide ion vacancies surrounding the Rh ion.
In 0.5 and 1 atom % Rh/CeO2, Rh is fully in the oxidized state, which is the real catalyst. The CO oxidation study has demonstrated that even 0.5 atom % Rh is sufficient to effect high catalytic activity. Therefore, Rh ion dispersed in CeO2 matrix is indeed the active site for CO + O2 oxidation. Also, air-heated 1 atom % Rh/CeO2 showed higher catalytic activity compared to the reduced catalyst. The higher surface concentration of Rh in the heat-treated catalyst compared to the reduced catalyst is in conformity with this observation, indicating oxidized Rh in CeO2 as the active site for CO oxidation.
The hydrogen uptake measurement demonstrated the unique interaction of Rh and CeO2 in terms of the decrease in reduction temperature from 180 C in pure Rh2O3 to 100  10 C in Rh/CeO2 catalysts. The oxygen storage capacity of Rh-substituted CeO2 is higher than that of pure CeO2, that too at much lower temperature. An H2/Rh ratio of 5.4, 2.4, 2.1, respectively, for 0.5, 1, and 2% Rh/CeO2 can definitely be attributed to contribution from the reduction of ceria at lower temperature, indicating a strong interaction between Rh and ceria. 32-34 This is to be expected, since oxide ion is bonded to both Rh3+ and Ce4+ ions in the solid solution model and reduction of Ce4+ to Ce3+ should occur to have a higher H2/Rh ratio. The observed reduction temperature over combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2 is lower by 65 C than the reported value by Fornasiero et al.34 over 0.5 wt % Rh/CeO2 prepared by the incipient wet impregnation method. The H2 consumption temperature of 167 C obtained by them is close to the Rh2O3 reduction temperature, suggesting the presence of oxidized rhodium in their catalyst.34
EXAFS studies show that Rh ions substitute for Ce4+ ions primarily on the surface in the form of Ce1-xRhxO2-δ solid solution. The enhanced surface concentration of Rh3+ in XPS indeed supports this point. In pure CeO2, the Ce4+OCe4+ correlation at 3.82 Å is due to CeOCe angle of 109.5. Due to substitution of the smaller Rh3+ ion, geometry around the Rh3+ ion will be different from Ce4+ in CeO2. Assuming an ionic radii of Rh3+ (0.665 Å), O2- (1.4 Å), and Ce4+ (1.01 Å), 35 for the RhCe distance of 3.16 Å the Rh3+OCe4+ angle would be 95. Similar correlations have been found by us in our earlier studies for Pd/CeO2, Cu/CeO2, and Pt/CeO2 systems at 3.31, 3.15, and 3.28 Å, respectively, in the form of Ce1-xMxO2-δ (M = Pd, Cu, and Pt) solid solution phase.11-13
Detailed structural and redox studies showed that in the combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2, RhCeO2 interaction is in the form of Ce1-xRhxO2-δ, mostly on the surface layers of CeO2. Since Rh is present in the +3 state in combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2, Rh3+ ions should be the active sites for CO adsorption in the CO + O2 reaction. For a higher rate of CO conversion at a lower temperature in the combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2, a higher amount of CO adsorption and availability of dissociated oxygen are essential. While Rh3+ ions can act as CO adsorption sites, additional oxygen adsorption sites would help achieve higher rates. Oxide ion vacancy, as demonstrated from both XRD and EXAFS studies, would be the natural oxygen adsorption sites next to Rh3+ ion sites. Therefore, lower temperature CO + O2 reaction over combustion-synthesized Rh/CeO2 is attributed to RhCeO2 interaction in the form of Ce1-xRhxO2-δ solid solution having Rh3+OCe4+O site distribution in the surface layers of the catalyst crystallites. Based on this Ce1-xRhxO2-δ model, we propose following redox mechanism for CO oxidation by O2.
In the above mechanism, one Rh3+ ion is reducing to Rh0, and conversion of Rh0 to Rh3+ via the holes (h•) created seems to reduce three Ce4+ to Ce3+. That Rh ion is going from 3+ to 0 and partial reduction of Ce4+ to Ce3+ are supported from TPR experiments with a H2/Rh ratio of more than what is needed to balance this equation. The oxygen vacancies (O2-••) seem to play a crucial role in the redox mechanism, and indeed both XRD and EXAFS has shown the presence of oxide ion vacancies. In the case of Cu/CeO2, Pd/CeO2, and Pt/CeO2, metal ion seems to go from +2 to 0 and correspondingly only two Ce ions gets reduced.10-12 Therefore, the lower concentration of Rh sufficient to bring about catalytic conversion supports the above mechanism.
The effect of addition of CeO2 and PMs in terms of higher catalytic activity (decrease in reaction temperature and higher rate of conversion) has been known for a long time, and it was generally attributed to strong metalsupport interaction. From this study, the actual interaction of Rh and CeO2 is shown to be ionicthat is, substitution of metal ion for Ce4+ ion in the reducible CeO2 support. The stabilization of Rh in ionic form over CeO2 certainly hinders sintering into Rh metal particles. Our study therefore explains the qualitative description in catalysis literature, namely, high dispersion, higher oxygen storage capacity, higher catalytic activity, and strong metalsupport interaction of Rh/CeO2 system.
Conclusions
(a) Rh dispersed in an ionic state over 50 nm CeO2 crystallites has been synthesized by the combustion technique.
(b) In comparison to Rh metal and Rh2O3, the Rh ions dispersed over CeO2 are more active for CO oxidation.
(c) H2/Rh ratio of 5.4, 2.4, and 2.1, respectively, for 0.5, 1, and 2% Rh/CeO2 suggests sufficiently high contribution from ceria reduction at lower temperature.
(d) Rietveld refinement confirms the absence of rhodium metal or rhodium oxide phases.
(e) TEM study shows absence of Rh metal particles in 0.5 and 1 atom % Rh/CeO2 catalyst.
(f) XPS and XANES studies of catalysts show that Rh is present in the ionic state.
(g) EXAFS analysis shows that Rh ion is substituted for Ce4+ ion in the surface layers of CeO2 crystallites with oxide ion vacancies around it.
(h) A Rh3+OCe4+ correlation at 3.16 Å in Rh/CeO2 catalysts has been shown from EXAFS analysis.
(i) The metalceria interaction in the form of Ce1-xRhxO2-δ solid solution mostly in the surface layersof CeO2 crystallites is responsible for enhanced catalytic activity.
